<BaseLayout
  title="Applied Linguistics & Motivation — Junqing (Jessie) Jia"
  description="Junqing Jia's research on second-language learning motivation: vision, socialization, and progression among learners of Chinese."
>
  <section class="shell measure section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Research</p>
    <h1>Applied Linguistics &amp; Motivation</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Why do some learners of Chinese keep going — through plateaus, across
      years, past the point where a grade requires it — while others stop? My
      research follows that question into the psychology of second-language
      motivation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="shell measure section">
    <h2>Research focus</h2>
    <p>
      I work in applied linguistics on the development of language-learning
      motivation, with a particular interest in what makes motivation
      <em>sustainable</em>. Rather than treating motivation as a fixed trait,
      I study it as something that is built and rebuilt over time — shaped by a
      learner's <strong>vision</strong> of a future self who uses the language,
      by <strong>socialization</strong> into communities where the language
      matters, and by a sense of <strong>progression</strong> that carries a
      learner from the classroom into real domains of use.
    </p>
    <p>
      A recurring theme in my work is helping learners <strong>perform beyond
      proficiency</strong>: establishing domain expertise so that Chinese
      becomes a tool for doing meaningful things, not only a subject to be
      studied. This bridges applied-linguistics theory and the day-to-day design
      of teaching — the thread that connects this work to my
      <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '')}/language-pedagogy/`}>language pedagogy</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

